thoughts.reasoning_problem:
Context: [BG] Books contain tons of knowledge. [BG] When a person reads a book, that person gains knowledge. [BG] If a person gains knowledge, they become smarter. Harry read the book “Walden” by Henry Thoreau.
Question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? A person who is smarter has gained knowledge.
Options: A) True B) False C) Uncertain
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
Contain(x, y) ::: x contains y.
Read(x, y) ::: x reads y.
Gain(x, y) ::: x gains y.
Smarter(x) ::: x is smarter.
Book(x) ::: x is a book.
Person(x) ::: x is a person.
Premises:
∀x (Book(x) → Contain(x, knowledge)) ::: Books contain tons of knowledge.
∀x ∀y (Person(x) ∧ Read(x, y) → Gain(x, knowledge)) ::: When a person reads a book, that person gains knowledge.
∀x (Person(x) ∧ Gain(x, knowledge) → Smarter(x)) ::: If a person gains knowledge, they become smarter.
Person(harry) ∧ Book(walden) ∧ Read(harry, walden) ::: Harry read the book “Walden” by Henry Thoreau.
Conclusion:
∀x (Person(x) ∧ Smarter(x) → Gain(x, knowledge)) ::: A person who is smarter has gained knowledge.
